    <text>
        <body>
            <div style="handwritten" type="letter" xml:id="d.1">
                <head type="title">Rutger Ressen to Miklós Oláh (Leuven, 27 December [1535])</head>
                <floatingText type="regesta">
                    <body>
                        <p xml:id="reg.p.1">He is sending Pieter Nanninck’s <hi rend="italic"
                                >Declamatio</hi>, which was presented here to great success. Why he
                            wants to dedicate it to Oláh, he will understand from Nanninck’s letter.
                            He is asking Oláh to review it as quickly as possible and send it back;
                            a bookseller wants to take some copies to France and England. </p>
                    </body>
                </floatingText>
                <pb/>
                <p xml:id="p.1">Rutgerus Rescius Nicolao Olao. </p>
                <p xml:id="p.2"><persName>Nannii</persName><note type="critic" xml:id="note.1"
                        >Pieter Nanninck (1496–1557) was born in Alkmaar. He first taught in Gouda,
                        then in 1535 he went to Leuven and succeeded Conrad Wackers as a Latin
                        teacher at the Collegium Trilingue in 1539. After Wacker left, Oláh looked
                        for a new tutor for John Henckel the Younger, and Nanninck was available.
                        Nanninck wrote commentaries on Horace’s <hi rend="italic">Ars Poetica</hi>,
                            <hi rend="italic">Aeneid</hi>, Livy, and translated many Greek authors,
                        for example, Plutarch and Athanasius. He also wrote a few works, mainly
                        declamations and speeches. On their friendship see <hi rend="smallcap"
                            >Polet</hi> 1936, 243–278; and <hi rend="smallcap">Tournoy</hi>
                        2006.</note> nostri <hi rend="italic">Declamationem</hi><note type="critic"
                        xml:id="note.2">Nanninck’s <hi rend="italic">Declamatio de bello Turcis
                            inferendo</hi> was published by Rutger Ressen, and it was dedicated to
                        Oláh, see <hi rend="smallcap">Nannius Alcmarianus</hi> 1536.</note> ad te
                    mitto, Domine Olahe plurimum Observande, quam hic proximo institio dixit et
                    frequentissimo auditorio et maximo omnium applausu. Eam quare tibi dedicare
                    decreverit, intelliges ex epistola ipsius ad te scripta.<note type="critic"
                        xml:id="note.3">See Ep. 554. This letter and the answers to it were
                        published at the beggining of the <hi rend="italic"
                            >Declamatio</hi>.<ref>olahus.tei.15351229_1</ref></note> Rogamus autem
                    Dominationem Tuam, ut quamprimum ipsam recognoveris, ilico ad nos remittas.
                    Cupit enim quidam bibliopola aliquot exemplaria ipsius mittere in Galliam et
                    Angliam. Bene valeat Dominatio Tua. Raptim. </p>
                <p xml:id="p.3"><placeName>Lovanii</placeName> in festo domini Ioannis Evangelistae. </p>
                <p xml:id="p.4"><persName>Magistrum Iacobum</persName><note type="critic"
                        xml:id="note.4">In ms. M. Iacobum, he was probably Jakob Jespersen.</note>
                    cupio salutari.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
